{"id":"2009.03132","submitter":"Thomas Kloss","authors":"Thomas Kloss, Joseph Weston, Benoit Gaury, Benoit Rossignol, Christoph\n  Groth, Xavier Waintal","title":"Tkwant: a software package for time-dependent quantum transport","comments":"26 pages, 14 figures, published version","journal-ref":"New J. Phys. 23, 023025 (2021)","doi":"10.1088/1367-2630/abddf7","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Tkwant is a Python package for the simulation of quantum nanoelectronics\ndevices to which external time-dependent perturbations are applied. Tkwant is\nan extension of the Kwant package (https://kwant-project.org/) and can handle\nthe same types of systems: discrete tight-binding-like models that consist of\nan arbitrary central region connected to semi-infinite electrodes. The problem\nis genuinely many-body even in the absence of interactions and is treated\nwithin the non-equilibrium Keldysh formalism. Examples of Tkwant applications\ninclude the propagation of plasmons generated by voltage pulses, propagation of\nexcitations in the quantum Hall regime, spectroscopy of Majorana fermions in\nsemiconducting nanowires, current-induced skyrmion motion in spintronic\ndevices, multiple Andreev reflection, Floquet topological insulators,\nthermoelectric effects, and more. The code has been designed to be easy to use\nand modular. Tkwant is free software distributed under a BSD license and can be\nfound at https://tkwant.kwant-project.org/.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 7 Sep 2020 14:37:26 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 3 Jan 2021 11:11:33 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 22 Feb 2021 12:24:08 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-02-23"}
